<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
   <title> Try It Yourself </title>
   <style type="text/css">
      input:checked {
         outline: 3px solid #903C56;
      }
      input:checked + label {
         color: #903C56;
      }
      #checkbox:checked {
         box-shadow: 2px 2px 4px 4px #903C56;
      }
      #checkbox:checked + label {
         box-shadow: 2px 2px 4px 4px #903C56;
      }
   </style>
</head>
<body>
   <p> The <b>:checked</b> CSS pseudo-class selector represents any... </p>
   <ul>
      <li><b>radio</b> (&lt;input
   type="radio"&gt;)</li>
      <li><b>checkbox</b> (&lt;input type="checkbox"&gt;)</li>
      <li><b>option</b> (&lt;option&gt; in a &lt;select&gt;) element</li>
   </ul>
   <p> ...that is checked or toggled to an on state. </p>
   
   <h3> Example: </h3>
   <form action="#">
      <p> Gender: </p>
      <div>
         <input type="radio" name="gender" id="male">
         <label for="male"> Male </label>
         <input type="radio" name="gender" id="female">
         <label for="female"> Female </label>
      </div>
      <p> Are you brilliant? </p>
      <div>
         <input type="checkbox" name="my-checkbox" id="checkbox" />
         <label for="checkbox"> Yes, I am! </label>
      </div>
   </form>
</body>
</html>